              <chunks count="1">
                <chunk name="Container">
                  <items count="8">
                    <item name="Description" type_name="gh_string" type_code="10">A panel for custom notes and text values</item>
                    <item name="InstanceGuid" type_name="gh_guid" type_code="9">d802ac55-5dcf-4e95-8026-3cd7ca97c52c</item>
                    <item name="Name" type_name="gh_string" type_code="10">Panel</item>
                    <item name="NickName" type_name="gh_string" type_code="10"></item>
                    <item name="Optional" type_name="gh_bool" type_code="1">false</item>
                    <item name="ScrollRatio" type_name="gh_double" type_code="6">0</item>
                    <item name="SourceCount" type_name="gh_int32" type_code="3">0</item>
                    <item name="UserText" type_name="gh_string" type_code="10">
Output Format: Update the damages inside the mesh object of the JSON.
3.  **Generate \`updatedModel\`**:
    *   Take the \`modelJson\` object as the base.
    *   You must iterate through **EVERY part** in the \`modelJson.parts\` array and analyze Surface, for each visible face, identify "coloration" (e.g., "white efflorescence/mortar") and "texture" (e.g., "pitted"). Analyze Edges and corners, look for "brokenness" or "material loss." 
    *   Based on your visual analysis of the photos and the user's text, identify any new damages.
    *   For each new damage, create a new damage object and add it to the list.
    *   Generate a new unique ID for each new damage (e.g., if the last was "damage_03", the new one is "damage_04").
    *   **Damage Object Schema**:
        - "id" (string): e.g., "damage_01"
        - "type" (string): "face" or "edge" or "vertex"
        - "vertices" (list): e.g., [0]
        - "status" (string): e.g., "Crack", "Brokenness", "Material Loss", "Discoloration"
        - "description" (string): A detailed sentence.
        - "coordinates" (object): { "x": number, "y": number, "z": number }, xaxis, yaxis
*   **Type Logic**:
Face if the damage is on the surface, edge if the damage is on an edge of the brick, vertex if the damage is in the corner of brick.
*   **Vertices Logic**:
If face the key of the face e.g. [0], if edge 2 vertices of the edge [0,1], if vertex the vertex key [1].
*   **Status Logic**:
Analyze surface for each visible face, identify "discoloration" (e.g., "white efflorescence/mortar") or "texture" (e.g., "pitted"), analyze edges and corners, look for "brokenness" or "material loss." </item>
                  </items>
